Key Contents
HTML, CSS, JavaScript Differences

HTML: Structures the web page content (text, images, buttons, etc.).

CSS: Handles the style and design of the web page (background color, fonts, layout, etc.).

JavaScript: Adds functionality to the web page (e.g., posting a tweet).

HTML Basic Structure
HTML is composed of tags. Tags are used in a format like <tagname>.

Most tags come in pairs: an opening tag (<tag>) and a closing tag (</tag>).

Tags without content can be used as self-closing tags (e.g., <img />).

Attributes can be added to tags to provide additional information (e.g., <img src="image.jpg">).

Essential Web Page Tags
<html>: The top-level tag that encloses the entire HTML document.

<head>: Includes the page's metadata (title, stylesheets, etc.).

<body>: Contains the content that the user actually sees on the web page.

<title>: Sets the title of the page that appears in the web browser tab.

Text-Related Tags
<h1> to <h6>: These are heading tags; the smaller the number, the more important the heading.

<p>: Represents a paragraph.

<strong>: Displays text in bold.

<em>: Displays text in italics.

<br>: Used for a line break.

Other Useful Tags
<button>: Creates a clickable button.

<ul> and <li>: Create an unordered list (bullet points).

<ol> and <li>: Create an ordered list (numbered list).







